# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advanced-economy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] Various organizations, including the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and global index providers such as MSCI and FTSE Russell, use their own methodologies to classify economies as "developed" or "advanced".
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] These may incorporate additional measures such as market accessibility, institutional quality, and financial market maturity.
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] Consequently, advanced economies are generally distinguished from emerging and developing economies not only by income levels, but also by the complexity, diversification, and stability of their economic systems.
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] The IMF maintains this classification primarily for analytical purposes, and some high-income economies particularly those heavily dependent on a single sector such as oil exports may still be categorized as emerging due to limited diversification.
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] As of April 2026, 43 economies are classified as advanced.
[src:advanced-economy/advanced-economy] These include major global economies such as the United States, Japan, and Germany, as well as smaller or highly specialized economies such as Singapore, the Republic of Ireland, and New Zealand.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is the sixth-smallest state in Europe, with an area of 468 square kilometres (181 sq mi) and a population of approximately 89,058 (as of February, 2026).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran people are a Romance group descended from the Catalans.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is the world's 17th-smallest country by land and 11th-smallest by population.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Its capital, Andorra la Vella, is the highest capital city in Europe, at an elevation of 1,023 metres (3,356 feet) above sea level.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The official language is Catalan, but Spanish, Portuguese, and French are also commonly spoken.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Tourism in Andorra brings approximately 8 million visitors to the country annually.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is not a member state of the European Union.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] It has been a member of the Council of Europe and of the United Nations since 1993.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The origin of the word Andorra is unknown, although several hypotheses have been proposed.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The oldest is one put forward by the Greek historian Polybius (*Histories* III, 35, 1), who describes the Andosins, an Iberian Pre-Roman tribe, as historically located in the valleys of Andorra and facing the Carthaginian army in its passage through the Pyrenees during the Punic Wars.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The word Andosini or Andosins (Ἀνδοσίνοι) may derive from the Basque *handia*, meaning "big" or "giant".
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran toponymy shows evidence of Basque language in the area.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Another theory suggests that the word Andorra may derive from the old word Anorra that contains the Basque word *ur* ("water").
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Another hypothesis suggests that Andorra may derive from Arabic *ad-dārra* (الدَّارَة), indicating a vast land which is located among mountains or a thickly wooded place (with *ad-* being the definite article).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] When the Moors conquered the Iberian Peninsula, the valleys of the High Pyrenees were covered by large tracts of forest.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] These regions were not administered by Muslims, because of the geographic difficulty of direct rule.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Other theories suggest that the term derives from the Navarro-Aragonese *andurrial*, which means "land covered with bushes" or "scrubland".
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The folk etymology holds that Charlemagne had named the region as a reference to the Biblical Canaanite valley of Endor or Andor (where the Midianites had been defeated), a name bestowed by his heir and son Louis the Pious after defeating the Moors in the "wild valleys of Hell".
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] La Balma de la Margineda, found by archaeologists at Sant Julià de Lòria, was settled in 9,500 BCE as a passing place between the two sides of the Pyrenees.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The seasonal camp was perfectly located for hunting and fishing by the groups of hunter-gatherers from Ariege and Segre.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During the Neolithic, a group of people moved to the Valley of Madriu (the present-day Natural Park located in Escaldes-Engordany declared UNESCO World Heritage Site) as a permanent camp in 6640 BCE.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The population of the valley grew cereals, raised domestic livestock, and developed commercial trade with people from Ségre and Occitania.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Other archaeological deposits include the Tombs of Segudet (Ordino) and Feixa del Moro (Sant Julià de Lòria), both dated in 4900–4300 BCE as an example of the Urn culture in Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The model of small settlements began to evolve to complex urbanism during the Bronze Age.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Metallurgical items of iron, ancient coins, and reliquaries can be found in the ancient sanctuaries scattered around the country.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The sanctuary of Roc de les Bruixes (Stone of the Witches) is perhaps the most important archaeological complex of this age in Andorra, located in the parish of Canillo, about the rituals of funerals, ancient scripture and engraved stone murals.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The inhabitants of the valleys were traditionally associated with the Iberians and historically located in Andorra as the Iberian tribe Andosins or Andosini (Ἀνδοσίνους) during the 7th and 2nd centuries BC.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Influenced by the Celtic, Aquitanian, Basque and Iberian languages, the locals developed some current toponyms.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Early writings and documents relating to this group of people goes back to the second century BC by the Greek writer Polybius in his *Histories* during the Punic Wars.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Some of the most significant remains of this era are the Castle of the Roc d'Enclar (part of the early Marca Hispanica), l'Anxiu in Les Escaldes and Roc de L'Oral in Encamp.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The presence of Roman influence is recorded from the 2nd century BCE to the 5th century CE.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The places with the most Roman presence are in Camp Vermell (Red Field) in Sant Julià de Lòria, and in some places in Encamp and in the Roc d'Enclar.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] People continued trading, mainly with wine and cereals, with the Roman cities of Urgellet (the present-day La Seu d'Urgell) and across Segre through the *via romana* Strata Ceretana (also known as Strata Confluetana).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After the fall of the Roman Empire, Andorra came under the influence of the Visigoths, the Kingdom of Toledo, and the Diocese of Urgell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Visigoths remained in the valleys for 200 years, during which time Christianity spread.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] When the Muslim Empire of Al-Andalus replaced the ruling Visigoths in most of the Iberian Peninsula, Andorra was under the jurisdiction of the Franks.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Tradition holds that Charles the Great (Charlemagne) granted a charter to the Andorran people for a contingent of 5,000 soldiers under the command of Marc Almugaver, in return for fighting against the Moors near Porté-Puymorens (Cerdanya).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra remained part of the Frankish *Marca Hispanica*, the buffer zone between the Frankish Empire and the Muslim territories, Andorra being part of the territory ruled by the Count of Urgell and eventually the bishop of the Diocese of Urgell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Tradition also holds that it was guaranteed by the son of Charlemagne, Louis the Pious, writing the *Carta de Poblament* or a local municipal charter c.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The first document that mentions Andorra as a territory is the *Acta de Consagració i Dotació de la Catedral de la Seu d'Urgell* (Deed of Consecration and Endowment of the Cathedral of La Seu d'Urgell).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The document, dated 839, depicts the six old parishes of the Andorran valleys that made up the country's administrative division.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 988, Count Borrell II of Urgell gave the Andorran valleys to the Diocese of Urgell in exchange for land in Cerdanya.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Since then, the bishop of Urgell, based in Seu d'Urgell, has been co-prince of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Before 1095, Andorra had no military protection, and the bishop of Urgell, who knew that the count of Urgell wanted to reclaim the Andorran valleys, asked the Lord of Caboet for help and protection.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1095, the lord of Caboet and the bishop of Urgell signed under oath a declaration of their co-sovereignty over Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Arnalda de Caboet, daughter of Arnau of Caboet, married the viscount of Castellbò.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Their daughter, Ermessenda de Castellbò, married the count of Foix, Roger-Bernard II.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Roger-Bernard II and Ermessenda shared rule over Andorra with the bishop of Urgell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In the 13th century, a military dispute arose between the bishop of Urgell and the count of Foix as aftermath of the Cathar Crusade.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] This gave the principality its territory and political form.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] A second paréage was signed in 1288 after a dispute when the count of Foix ordered the construction of a castle in Roc d'Enclar.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The document was ratified by the noble notary Jaume Orig of Puigcerdà, and construction of military structures in the country was prohibited.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1364, the political organisation of the country named the figure of the syndic (now spokesman and president of the parliament) as representative of the Andorrans to their co-princes, making possible the creation of local departments (comuns, quarts and veïnats).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After being ratified by Bishop Francesc Tovia and Count John I, the Consell de la Terra or Consell General de les Valls (General Council of the Valleys) was founded in 1419, the second oldest parliament in Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The syndic Andreu d'Alàs and the General Council organised the creation of the Justice Courts (La Cort de Justicia) in 1433 with the co-princes and the collection of taxes like foc i lloc (literally "fire and site", a national tax active since then).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Catalan Pyrenees were embryonic of the Catalan language at the end of the 11th century.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra was influenced by this language, which was adopted locally decades before it expanded to the rest of the Crown of Aragon.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The local economy during the Middle Ages was based on livestock, agriculture, furs and weavers.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Later, at the end of the 11th century, the first iron foundries began to appear in Northern Parishes like Ordino, much appreciated by the master artisans who developed the art of the forges, an important economic activity in the country from the 15th century.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1601 the Tribunal de Corts (High Court of Justice) was created as a result of Huguenot rebellions in France, Inquisition courts coming from Spain and witchcraft-related beliefs native to the area, in the context of the Reformation and Counter-Reformation.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] With the passage of time, the co-title to Andorra passed to the kings of Navarre.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After Henry III of Navarre became king of France, he issued an edict in 1607 that established the head of the French state and the bishop of Urgell as co-lords of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] From the last quarter of the 17th century onwards, as political ties with the Principality of Catalonia and the Monarchy of Spain progressively weakened, the co-lords began to be referred and act as "co-princes" (sovereigns), a political arrangement that still holds.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During 1617, communal councils form the sometent (popular militia or army) to deal with the rise of bandolerisme (brigandage) and the Consell de la Terra was defined and structured in terms of its composition, organisation and competences current today.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra continued with the same economic system that it had during the 12th–14th centuries with a large production of metallurgy (fargues, a system similar to Farga Catalana) and with the introduction of tobacco circa 1692 and import trade.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1371 and 1448, the co-princes ratified the fair of Andorra la Vella, the most commercially important annual national festival ever since.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The country had a unique and experienced guild of weavers, Confraria de Paraires i Teixidors, in Escaldes-Engordany.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Founded in 1604, it took advantage of the local thermal waters.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] By this time, the country was characterised by the social system of prohoms (wealthy society) and casalers (rest of the population with smaller economic acquisition), deriving from the tradition of pubilla and hereu.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Three centuries after its foundation, the Consell de la Terra located its headquarters and the Tribunal de Corts in Casa de la Vall in 1702.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The manor house built in 1580 served as a noble fortress of the Busquets family.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Inside the parliament was placed the Closet of the Six Keys (Armari de les sis claus), representative of each Andorran parish, where the Andorran constitution and other documents and laws were later kept.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In both the Reapers' War and the War of the Spanish Succession, the Andorran people (while professing to be a neutral country) supported the rest of the Catalans who ultimately saw most of their rights suppressed in 1716 as a consequence of the promulgation of the Nueva Planta decrees.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Another direct reaction to the events was the promotion of Catalan writings in Andorra, with cultural works such as the *Book of Privileges* (*Llibre de Privilegis de 1674*), *Manual Digest* (1748) by Antoni Fiter i Rossell or the *Polità andorrà* (1763) by Antoni Puig.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After the French Revolution, Napoleon I reestablished the Co-Principate in 1809 and removed the French medieval title.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1812–1813, the First French Empire annexed Catalonia during the Peninsular War (*Guerra Peninsular*) and divided the region into four departements, with Andorra as a part of the district of Puigcerdà.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1814, an imperial decree reestablished the independence and economy of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During this period, Andorra's late medieval institutions and rural culture remained largely unchanged.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1866, the syndic Guillem d'Areny-Plandolit led the reformist group in a Council General of 24 members elected by suffrage limited to heads of families.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Council General replaced the aristocratic oligarchy that previously ruled the state.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The New Reform (*Nova Reforma*) began after ratification by both Co-Princes and established the basis of the constitution and symbols – such as the tricolour flag – of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] A new service economy arose as a demand of the valley inhabitants and began to build infrastructure such as hotels, spa resorts, roads and telegraph lines.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The authorities of the Co-Princes banned casinos and betting houses throughout the country.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The ban resulted in an economic conflict and the Revolution of 1881, which began when revolutionaries assaulted the house of the syndic on 8 December 1880, and established the Provisional Revolutionary Council led by Joan Pla i Calvo and Pere Baró i Mas.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Provisional Revolutionary Council allowed for the construction of casinos and spas by foreign companies.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] From 7 to 9 June 1881, the loyalists of Canillo and Encamp reconquered the parishes of Ordino and La Massana by establishing contact with the revolutionary forces in Escaldes-Engordany.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After a day of combat the Treaty of the Bridge of Escalls was signed on 10 June.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The council was replaced and new elections were held.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The economic situation worsened, as the populace was divided over the *Qüestió d'Andorra* – the "Andorran Question".
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The struggles continued between pro-bishops, pro-French, and nationalists based on the troubles of Canillo in 1882 and 1885.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra participated in the cultural movement of the Catalan Renaixença.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Between 1882 and 1887, the first academic schools were formed where trilingualism coexisted with the official language, Catalan.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Romantic authors from France and Spain reported the awakening of the national consciousness of the country.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Jacint Verdaguer lived in Ordino during the 1880s where he wrote and shared works related to the Renaixença with writer and photographer Joaquim de Riba.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1848, Fromental Halévy had premiered the opera *Le val d'Andorre* to great success in Europe, where the national consciousness of the valleys was exposed in the romantic work during the Peninsular War.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] On 5 April 1933 Joves Andorrans seized the Andorran Parliament.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] These actions were preceded by the arrival of Colonel René-Jules Baulard with 50 gendarmes and the mobilisation of 200 local militias or sometent led by the Síndic Francesc Cairat.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] On 8 July 1934 Boris issued a proclamation in Urgell, declaring himself Boris I, King of Andorra, simultaneously declaring war on the Bishop of Urgell and approving the King's constitution on 10 July.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] He was arrested by the Co-Prince and Bishop Justí Guitart i Vilardebó and their authorities on 20 July and ultimately expelled from Spain.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During the Spanish Civil War, the inhabitants of Andorra welcomed refugees from both sides, and many of them settled permanently in the country thus contributing to the subsequent economic boom and the entry into the capitalist era of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Francoist troops reached the Andorran border in the later stages of the war.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During World War II, Andorra remained neutral and was an important smuggling route between Vichy France and Francoist Spain.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Many Andorrans criticised the passivity of the General Council for impeding both the entry and expulsion of foreigners and refugees, committing economic crimes, reducing the rights of citizens and sympathy with Francoism.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] General Council members justified the council's political and diplomatic actions as necessary for Andorra's survival and the protection of its sovereignty.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra was relatively unscathed by the two world wars and the Spanish Civil War.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Certain groups formed to help victims of oppression in Nazi-occupied countries, while participating in smuggling to help Andorra survive.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Among the most prominent was the Hostal Palanques Evasion Network Command, which, in contact with the British MI6, helped almost 400 fugitives, among whom were Allied military personnel.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Command remained active between 1941 and 1944, although there were struggles with pro-Axis informers and Gestapo agents in Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The network was maintained after the war, when film societies were formed, where movies, music and books censored in Franco's Spain were imported, becoming an anti-censorship attraction for the Catalan or foreign public even within Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran Group (Agrupament Andorrà), an anti-fascist organisation linked to the Occitanie's French Resistance, accused the French representative (veguer) of collaboration with Nazism.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran opening to the capitalist economy resulted in two axes: mass tourism and the country's tax exemption.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The first steps towards the capitalist boom date from the 1930s, with the construction of FHASA and the creation of professional banking with Banc Agrícol (1930) and Crèdit Andorrà (1949), later with Banca Mora (1952), Banca Cassany (1957) and SOBANCA (1960).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Shortly after, activities such as skiing and shopping helped the country become a tourist attraction, with the inauguration of ski resorts and cultural entities in the late 1930s.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] A revived hotel industry also developed.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In April 1968 a social health insurance system was created (CASS).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra experienced an era commonly known as the "Andorran dream" (similar to the American Dream) along with the Trente Glorieuses: mass culture rooted itself in the country experiencing radical changes in the economy and culture.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Proof of this was Ràdio Andorra, the top musical radio station in Europe in this period, with guests and speakers of great importance promoting musical hits from chanson française, swing, rhythm & blues, jazz, rock and roll and American country music.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During this period Andorra achieved a GDP per capita and a life expectancy higher than most standard countries of the time.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Given its relative isolation, Andorra has existed outside the mainstream of European history, with few ties to countries other than France, Spain and Portugal.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] But in recent times its thriving tourist industry, along with developments in transport and communications, have removed the country from its isolation.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Since 1976 the country has seen the need to reform Andorran institutions due to anachronisms in sovereignty, human rights and the balance of powers as well as the need to adapt legislation to modern demands.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1982 a first separation of powers took place when instituting the Govern d'Andorra, under the name of the executive board (Consell Executiu), chaired by the first prime minister Òscar Ribas Reig with the co-princes' approval.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 1989 the Principality signed an agreement with the European Economic Community to regularise trade relations.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Its political system was modernised in 1993 after the Andorran constitutional referendum, when the constitution was drafted by the co-princes and the General Council and approved on 14 March by 74.2% of voters, with a 76% turnout.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The first elections under the new constitution were held later in the year.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The same year, Andorra became a member of the United Nations and the Council of Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra formalised diplomatic relations with the United States in 1996, participating in the 51st UN General Assembly.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] First General Syndic Marc Forné took part in a speech in Catalan in the General Assembly to defend the reform of the organisation, and after three days he took part in the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe to defend Andorra's linguistic rights and economy.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 2004, the Madriu-Perafita-Claror Valley was enlisted as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, making it Andorra's first site, for its ancient pastoralism, communal land-use and ironworking traditions.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 2006 a monetary agreement with the European Union was formalised that allows Andorra to use the euro officially, as well as minting its own euro coins.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Due to its location in the eastern Pyrenees mountain range, Andorra consists predominantly of rugged mountains, the highest being the Coma Pedrosa at 2,946 metres (9,665 ft), and the average elevation of Andorra is 1,996 metres (6,549 ft).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] These are dissected by three narrow valleys in a Y shape that combine into one as the main stream, the Gran Valira river, leaves the country for Spain (at Andorra's lowest point of 840 m or 2,756 ft).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra's land area is 468 km2 (181 sq mi).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Phytogeographically, Andorra belongs to the Atlantic European province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Andorra belongs to the ecoregion of Pyrenees conifer and mixed forests.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 4.45/10, ranking it 127th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In Andorra forest cover is around 34% of the total land area, equivalent to 16,000 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which was unchanged from 1990.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 16,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 0 hectares (ha).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The whole country has been recognised by BirdLife International as a single Important Bird Area (IBA), known as *Pirineo de Andorra*.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] It is important for forest and high-mountain birds and supports significant populations of red-billed choughs, citril finches and rock buntings.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra has alpine, continental and oceanic climates, depending on altitude.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Its higher elevation means there is, on average, more snow in winter and it is slightly cooler in summer.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The diversity of landmarks, the different orientation of the valleys and the irregularity relief typical of the Mediterranean climates make the country have a great diversity of microclimates that hinder the general dominance of the high mountain climate.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The great differences of altitude in the minimum and maximum points, together with the influence of a Mediterranean climate, develop the climate of the Andorran Pyrenees.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] When in precipitation, a global model characterised by convective and abundant rains can be defined during spring and summer, which can last until autumn (May, June and August are usually the rainiest months).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In winter, however, it is less rainy, except in the highlands, subject to the influence of fronts from the Atlantic, which explains the great amount of snowfall in the Andorran mountains.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The temperature regime is characterised, broadly, by a temperate summer and a long and cold winter, in accordance with the mountainous condition of the Principality.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] As a small mountainous country, Andorra is highly vulnerable to climate change.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Temperatures in its high-altitude regions have risen by about 0.17 °C per decade, while annual rainfall has decreased by 49 mm.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] These shifts are impacting water resources and snow cover, which are key elements for Andorra's tourism-driven economy.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The number of days with enough snow for skiing is declining, and the snow line is retreating to higher altitudes.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Although its national greenhouse gas emissions are one of the lowest in the world (534 thousand tonnes emitted in 2023), Andorra has a strong climate change mitigation strategy, with a focus on renewable energy and energy efficiency.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In its Nationally Determined Contribution, Andorra has committed to reducing its emissions by 55% by 2030, and to carbon neutrality by 2050.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] However, the adaptation part of the strategy is still in early stages and may be difficult and costly to implement.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Given the country's reliance on tourism, speeding up adaptation is essential for building a more resilient economy.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is a unitary co-principality governed as a parliamentary constitutional diarchy, with the bishop of Urgell and the president of France as co-princes.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] This peculiarity makes the president of France, in his capacity as prince of Andorra, an elected monarch, although he is not elected by a popular vote of the Andorran people.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The politics of Andorra take place in a framework of a parliamentary representative democracy with a unicameral legislature, and of a pluriform multi-party system.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The prime minister is the chief executive.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The current prime minister is Xavier Espot Zamora of the Democrats for Andorra (DA).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Executive power is exercised by the government.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Legislative power is vested in both government and parliament.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Parliament of Andorra is known as the General Council.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The General Council consists of between 28 and 42 councillors.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The councillors serve for four-year terms, and elections are held between the 30th and 40th days following the dissolution of the previous Council.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Half are elected in equal numbers by each of the seven administrative parishes, and the other half of the councillors are elected in a single national constituency.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Voters vote for parties, not candidates; a voter votes for a party for the parish councillors and a party for the at-large councilors, and the winners come from party lists.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Fifteen days after the election, the councillors hold their inauguration.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During this session, the General Syndic, who is the head of the General Council, and the Subsyndic General, his assistant, are elected.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Eight days later, the Council convenes once more.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] During this session, the prime minister is chosen from among the councillors.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Candidates can be proposed by a minimum of one-fifth of the councillors.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Council then elects the candidate with the absolute majority of votes to be prime minister.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Syndic General then notifies the co-princes, who in turn appoint the elected candidate as the prime minister of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The General Council is also responsible for proposing and passing laws.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Bills may be presented to the council as Private Members' Bills by three of the local Parish Councils jointly or by at least one tenth of the citizens of Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The council also approves the annual budget of the principality.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The government must submit the proposed budget for parliamentary approval at least two months before the previous budget expires.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] If the budget is not approved by the first day of the next year, the previous budget is extended until a new one is approved.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Once any bill is approved, the Syndic General is responsible for presenting it to the co-princes so that they may sign and enact it.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] If the prime minister is not satisfied with the council, he may request that the co-princes dissolve the council and order new elections.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In turn, the councillors have the power to remove the prime minister from office.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After a motion of censure is approved by at least one-fifth of the councillors, the council will vote and if it receives the absolute majority of votes, the prime minister is removed.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is a full member of the United Nations (UN), the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), and has a special agreement with the European Union (EU).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] After the constitution was ratified, Andorra would later establish diplomatic relations with their major allies aside from neighbours France and Spain such as the United Kingdom in 1994 and the United States in 1995.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] It also has observer status at the World Trade Organisation (WTO).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] On 16 October 2020, Andorra became the 190th member of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra's current foreign minister is Imma Tor Faus.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Their representative to the United Nations is Joan Forner Rovira.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra is one of the 46 member states of the Council of Europe, having joined on 10 November 1994.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] For 2025, the Council of Europe's budget is €655.7 million, with Andorra contributing €368,842.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra does not have its own standing armed forces, and responsibility for defending the principality rests primarily with France and Spain.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In emergencies or natural disasters, however, the Sometent (an alarm) is called, and all able-bodied Andorran men between the ages of 21 and 60 are liable for service.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] For that reason, the head of each household, traditionally the eldest able-bodied man, is legally expected to keep a rifle, although the law also provides that the police may supply a firearm if required.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Historically, Andorra's defence system was based not on a permanent army but on the principle that able-bodied men could be summoned when needed through the Sometent, a civil defence organisation made up of heads of household.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Sometent was used only sparingly, including against French "Lutheran" raids in the late 16th century.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] As a landlocked country, Andorra has never had a navy.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Before World War I, Andorra maintained an armed militia force of about 600 part-time militiamen under the supervision of a Captain (Capità or Cap de Sometent) and a Lieutenant (Desener or Lloctinent del Capità).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] This force was not liable for service outside the principality and was commanded by two officials (*veguers*) appointed by France and the Bishop of Urgell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] In the modern period, Andorra's military role was reduced to a very small body of volunteers willing to perform ceremonial duties, with uniforms and weaponry often handed down through families and communities.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Responsibility for internal security largely passed to the Police Corps of Andorra after its creation in 1931.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Civil unrest linked to the elections of 1933 led to assistance being requested from the French National Gendarmerie, which maintained a detachment in Andorra for two months under the command of René-Jules Baulard.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran Police was reorganised the following year, with eleven soldiers appointed to supervisory roles.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The force included six corporals, one for each parish, together with four junior staff officers and a commander holding the rank of major.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Each corporal was responsible for being able to raise a fighting force from the able-bodied men of his parish.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] At present, the only permanent element of the Sometent is a twelve-man ceremonial unit.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Even so, all able-bodied men remain technically available for military service, and each household is still required to have access to a firearm.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] An area weapon, such as a shotgun per household, is unregulated; however, ranged weapons, such as pistols and rifles, require a licence.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The army has not fought for more than 700 years, and its principal modern role is to present the flag of Andorra at official ceremonial functions.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] According to Marc Forné Molné, Andorra's military budget is funded entirely by voluntary donations and the availability of full-time volunteers.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The most recent general emergency call to the Sometent came during the floods of 1982 in the Catalan Pyrenees, when 12 Andorran citizens died; the force was mobilised to assist the population and help maintain public order alongside local police units.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Andorra maintains a small but modern and well-equipped internal police force, with around 240 police officers supported by civilian assistants.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The principal services supplied by the corps are uniformed community policing, criminal detection, border control, and traffic policing.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] There are also small specialist units including police dogs, mountain rescue, and a bomb disposal team.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The *Grup d'Intervenció Policia d'Andorra*' (GIPA) is a small special forces squad trained in counter-terrorism, and hostage recovery tasks.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Although it is the closest in style to an active military force, it is part of the Police Corps, and not the army.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] As terrorist and hostage situations are a rare threat to the country, the GIPA is commonly assigned to prisoner escort duties, and at other times to routine policing.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Andorran Fire Brigade, with headquarters at Santa Coloma, operates from four modern fire stations, and has a staff of around 120 firefighters.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The service is equipped with 16 heavy appliances (fire tenders, turntable ladders, and specialist four-wheel drive vehicles), four light support vehicles (cars and vans) and four ambulances.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Historically, the families of the six ancient parishes of Andorra maintained local arrangements to assist each other in fighting fires.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The first fire pump purchased by the government was acquired in 1943.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] Serious fires which lasted for two days in December 1959 led to calls for a permanent fire service, and the Andorran Fire Brigade was formed on 21 April 1961.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The fire service maintains full-time cover with five fire crews on duty at any time: two at the brigade's headquarters in Santa Coloma, and one crew at each of the other three fire stations.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The judiciary is composed of the Magistrates Court, the Criminal Law Court, the High Court of Andorra, and the Constitutional Court.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The High Court of Justice is composed of five judges: one appointed by the prime minister, one each by the co-princes, one by the Syndic General, and one by the judges and magistrates.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] It is presided over by the member appointed by the Syndic General and the judges hold office for six-year terms.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The magistrates and judges are appointed by the High Court, as is the president of the Criminal Law Court.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The High Court also appoints members of the Office of the Attorney General.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Constitutional Court is responsible for interpreting the Constitution and reviewing all appeals of unconstitutionality against laws and treaties.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] It is composed of four judges, one appointed by each of the co-princes and two by the General Council.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p01] The Court is presided over by one of the judges on a two-year rotation so that each judge at one point will preside over the Court.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Tourism, the mainstay of Andorra's economy, accounts for roughly 80% of GDP.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] An estimated 8 million tourists visit annually, attracted by Andorra's duty-free status and by its summer and winter resorts.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] One of the main sources of income in Andorra is from ski resorts, which total over 175 km (109 mi) of ski grounds.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The sport brings in over 7 million visitors annually and an estimated 340 million euros per year, sustaining 2,000 direct and 10,000 indirect jobs at present since 2007.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The banking sector, with its tax haven status, also contributes substantially to the economy with revenues raised exclusively through import tariffs (the financial and insurance sector accounts for approximately 19% of GDP).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] However, during the Euro area crisis, the tourist industry suffered a decline, partly caused by a drop in the prices of goods in Spain, undercutting duty-free shopping and increasing unemployment.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] On 1 January 2012, a business tax of 10% was introduced, followed by a sales tax of 2% a year later, which raised just over 14 million euros in its first quarter.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Agricultural production is limited; only 1.7% of the land is arable, and most food has to be imported.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The principal livestock activity is domestic sheep raising.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Manufacturing output consists mainly of cigarettes, cigars, and furniture.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra's natural resources include hydroelectric power, mineral water, timber, iron ore, and lead.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra is not a member of the European Union, but enjoys a special relationship with it, such as being treated as an EU member for trade in manufactured goods (no tariffs) and as a non-EU member for agricultural products.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra lacked a currency of its own and used both the French franc and the Spanish peseta in banking transactions until 31 December 1999, when both currencies were replaced by the EU's single currency, the euro.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Coins and notes of both the franc and the peseta remained legal tender in Andorra until 31 December 2002.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra negotiated to issue its own euro coins, beginning in early 2015.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra has historically had one of the world's lowest unemployment rates.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] On 31 May 2013, it was announced that Andorra intended to legislate for the introduction of an income tax by the end of June, against a background of increasing dissatisfaction with the existence of tax havens among EU members.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The announcement was made following a meeting in Paris between the Prime Minister Antoni Martí and the French President and Prince of Andorra François Hollande.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Hollande welcomed the move as part of a process of Andorra "bringing its taxation in line with international standards".
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The last mergers between banks took place in 2022, bringing the Andorran financial sector to currently have 3 active banking groups.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Skiing, hiking, cross-country running, and cycling are all popular sports tourism activities in Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra's economy is heavily built on tourism.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra's ski season usually goes from late November to early April, depending on weather conditions.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] This peak is part of the Tristaina cirque, along with the Costa Rodona, Tristaina, Creussans, and Cabanyó peaks.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In Andorra, mobile and fixed telephone and internet services are operated exclusively by the Andorran national telecommunications company, SOM, also known as Andorra Telecom (STA).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The same company also manages the technical infrastructure for national broadcasting of digital television and radio.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 2010 Andorra became the first country to provide a direct optical fibre link to all homes (FTTH) and businesses.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Until the 20th century, Andorra had very limited transport links to the outside world, and development of the country was affected by its physical isolation.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra has a road network of 279 km (173 mi), of which 76 km (47 mi) is unpaved.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The two main roads out of Andorra la Vella are the CG-1 to the Spanish border near Sant Julià de Lòria, and the CG-2 to the French border via the Envalira Tunnel near El Pas de la Casa.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Bus services cover all metropolitan areas and many rural communities, with services on most major routes running half-hourly or more frequently during peak travel times.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are frequent long-distance bus services from Andorra to Barcelona and Toulouse, plus a daily tour from the former city.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Bus services mostly are run by private companies, but some local ones are operated by the government.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Since July 2015, Andorra–La Seu d'Urgell Airport has operated commercial flights to Madrid and Palma de Mallorca, and is the main hub for Andorra Airlines.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Nearby airports located in Spain and France provide access to international flights for the principality.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The nearest international airports are Toulouse-Blagnac Airport, located 195 km (121 mi) north, and Josep Tarradellas Barcelona-El Prat Airport, located 198 km (123 mi) south east from Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are hourly bus services from both Barcelona and Toulouse airports to Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The nearest railway station is Andorre-L'Hospitalet station 10 km (6 mi) east of Andorra which is on the 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in)-gauge line from Latour-de-Carol (25 km or 16 mi) southeast of Andorra, to Toulouse and on to Paris by the French high-speed trains.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Latour-de-Carol has a scenic 1,000 mm (3 ft 3+3⁄8 in) metre gauge trainline to Villefranche-de-Conflent, as well as the SNCF's 1,435 mm-gauge line connecting to Perpignan, and the Renfe's 1,668 mm (5 ft 5+21⁄32 in) -gauge line to Barcelona.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are also direct Intercités de nuit trains between L'Hospitalet-près-l'Andorre and Paris on certain dates.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The population of Andorra is estimated at 79,034 (2021).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Andorrans are a Romance ethnic group of originally Catalan descent.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The population has grown from 5,000 in 1900.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Two-thirds of residents lack Andorran nationality and do not have the right to vote in communal elections.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Moreover, they are not allowed to be elected as prime minister or to own more than 33% of the capital stock of a privately held company.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The largest national groups in Andorra are Spanish (34.3%), Andorrans (32.1%), Portuguese (10%), and French (5.6%).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The remaining 18% of the population includes British, Dutch, Germans, Italians and other Europeans, as well as Argentinians, Chileans, Indians, Moroccans and Uruguayans.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Population growth in Andorra in mainly due to young workers finding jobs in the tourism, hospitality and services sectors.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Recent waves of immigrations come from South America, mainly Colombia and Peru.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The historic and official language is Catalan, a Romance language.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Andorran government encourages the use of Catalan.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] It funds a Commission for Catalan Toponymy in Andorra (Catalan: *Comissió de Toponímia d'Andorra*), and provides free Catalan classes to assist immigrants.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorran television and radio stations use Catalan.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Because of immigration, historical links, and close geographic proximity, Spanish, Portuguese and French are commonly spoken.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Most Andorran residents can speak one or more of these, in addition to Catalan.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] English is less commonly spoken among the general population, though it is understood to varying degrees in the major tourist resorts.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra is one of only four European countries (together with France, Monaco, and Turkey) that have never signed the Council of Europe Framework Convention on National Minorities.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Few official statistics are available on religion.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The CIA World Factbook estimates the Catholic population in 2020 at 89.5%.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Statistical Yearbook of the Catholic Church 2022 reports that 98.6% of the population were baptised Catholics.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The patron saint is Our Lady of Meritxell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are also members of various Protestant denominations and small numbers of Hindus, and Bahá'ís.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 2022 there were approximately 2000 Muslims and roughly 100 Jews.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Qualified Education Law (*llei qualificada d'educació*) of Andorra was passed in 1993.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] It guarantees free, public education from age four until the end of compulsory schooling.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Children between the ages of 6 and 16 are required by law to have full-time education.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Education up to secondary level is provided free of charge by the government.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are three systems of school, Andorran, French and Spanish, which use Catalan, French and Spanish languages respectively, as the main language of instruction.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Parents may choose which system their children attend.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] All schools are built and maintained by Andorran authorities, but teachers in the French and Spanish schools are paid for the most part by France and Spain.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] 39% of Andorran children attend Andorran schools, 33% attend French schools, and 28% Spanish schools.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Universitat d'Andorra (UdA) is the state public university and is the only university in Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The university provides first-level degrees in nursing, computer science, business administration, and educational sciences, in addition to higher professional education courses.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The only two graduate schools in Andorra are the Nursing School and the School of Computer Science, the latter having a PhD programme.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The geographical complexity of the country as well as the small number of students prevents the University of Andorra from developing a full academic programme, and it serves principally as a centre for virtual studies, connected to Spanish and French universities.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The centre also runs various postgraduate programmes and continuing-education courses for professionals.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra is home to folk dances like the contrapàs and marratxa, which survive in Sant Julià de Lòria especially.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorran folk music has similarities to the music of its neighbours, but is especially Catalan in character, especially in the presence of dances such as the sardana.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Other Andorran folk dances include contrapàs in Andorra la Vella and Saint Anne's dance in Escaldes-Engordany.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra's national holiday is Our Lady of Meritxell Day, 8 September.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra participated regularly in the Eurovision Song Contest between 2004 and 2009, being the only participating country presenting songs in Catalan.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In popular folklore, the best-known Andorran legends are the legend of Charlemagne, according to which this Frankish king would have founded the country, the White Lady of Auvinyà, the Buner d'Ordino, the legend of Engolasters Lake and the legend of Our Lady of Meritxell.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorran gastronomy is mainly Catalan, although it has also adopted other elements of French and Italian cuisines.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The cuisine of the country has similar characteristics with the neighbours of Cerdanya and Alt Urgell, with which it has strong cultural ties.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra's cuisine is defined by its mountain valleys.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] To drink, mulled wine and beer are also popular.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Some of the dishes are very common in the mountainous regions of Catalonia, such as trinxat, embotits, cooked snails, rice with mushrooms, mountain rice and mató.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Pre-Romanesque and Romanesque art are some of the most important artistic manifestations and characteristics of the Principality.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Romanesque style helps to understand the formation of the parochial communities, the relations of (social and political) power and the national culture.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are a total of forty Romanesque churches that stand out as being small austere ornamentation constructions, as well as bridges, fortresses and manor houses of the same period.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Summer solstice fire festivals in the Pyrenees were included as UNESCO Intangible cultural heritage in 2015.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Also, the Madriu-Perafita-Claror Valley became Andorra's first, and to date its only, UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2004, with a small extension in 2006.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There are three national newspapers, *Diari d'Andorra*, *El Periòdic d'Andorra*, and *Bondia*, as well as several local newspapers.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The history of the Andorran press begins in the period between 1917 and 1937 with the appearance of several periodicals such as *Les Valls d'Andorra* (1917), *Nova Andorra* (1932), and *Andorra Agrícola* (1933).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 1974, the *Poble Andorrà* became the first regular newspaper in Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] There is also an amateur radio society and news agency ANA with independent management.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The first commercial radio station to broadcast was Radio Andorra, which was active from 1939 to 1981.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] On 12 October 1989, the General Council established radio and television as essential public services creating and managing the entity ORTA, becoming on 13 April 2000, in the public company Ràdio i Televisió d'Andorra (RTVA).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 1990, the public radio was founded on the Radio Nacional d'Andorra.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] As an autochthonous television channel, there is only the national public television network Andorra Televisió, created in 1995.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Additional TV and radio stations from Spain and France are available via digital terrestrial television and IPTV.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra is well known for its winter sports.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra has the largest territory of ski slopes in the Pyrenees (3100 hectares and about 350 km of slopes) and two ski resorts.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Grandvalira is the largest and busiest resort.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Other sports commonly played in Andorra include football, rugby union, basketball, and roller hockey.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In roller hockey, Andorra usually plays in the CERH Euro Cup and FIRS Roller Hockey World Cup.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 2011, Andorra was the host country to the 2011 European League Final Eight.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The country is represented in association football by the Andorra national football team.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The team gained its first competitive win in a European Championship qualifier on 11 October 2019, against Moldova.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Football is governed in Andorra by the Andorran Football Federation; founded in 1994, it organises the national competitions of association football (Primera Divisió, Copa Constitució and Supercopa), and futsal.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra was admitted to UEFA and FIFA in 1996.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] FC Andorra, a club based in Andorra la Vella founded in 1942, compete in the Spanish football league system.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Rugby is a traditional sport in Andorra, mainly influenced by its popularity in southern France.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Andorra national rugby union team, nicknamed Els Isards, plays on the international stage in rugby union and rugby sevens.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] VPC Andorra XV is a rugby team based in Andorra la Vella, which actually plays in the French championship.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Basketball's popularity has increased in the country since the 1990s, when the Andorran team BC Andorra played in the top league of Spain (Liga ACB).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] After 18 years the club returned to the top league in 2014.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Other sports practised in Andorra include cycling, volleyball, judo, Australian rules football, handball, swimming, gymnastics, tennis, and motorsports.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] In 2012, Andorra raised its first national cricket team and played a home match against the Dutch Fellowship of Fairly Odd Places Cricket Club, the first match played in the history of Andorra at an altitude of 1,300 metres (4,300 ft).
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra first participated at the Olympic Games in 1976.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The country has appeared in every Winter Olympic Games since 1976.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] Andorra competes in the Games of the Small States of Europe, being the host country on three occasions, in 1991, 2005 and 2025.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] As one of the Catalan Countries, Andorra is home to a team of castellers, or Catalan human tower builders.
[src:advanced-economy/andorra-p02] The Castellers d'Andorra, based in the town of Santa Coloma d'Andorra, are recognised by the Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya, the governing body of castells.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:advanced-economy/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The area of today's Austria has been inhabited since at least the Paleolithic period.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Around 400 BC, it was inhabited by the Celts and then annexed by the Romans in the late 1st century BC.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Christianization in the region began in the 4th and 5th centuries, during the late Roman period, followed by the arrival of numerous Germanic tribes during the Migration Period.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria, as an unified state, emerged from the remnants of the Eastern and Hungarian March at the end of the first millennium, first as a frontier march of the Holy Roman Empire, it then developed into a Duchy in 1156, and was made an Archduchy in 1453.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Being the heartland of the Habsburg monarchy since the late 13th century, Austria was a major imperial power in Central Europe for centuries and from the 16th century, Vienna also served as the Holy Roman Empire's administrative capital.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Holy Roman Empire was dissolved in 1806, two years after Austria had established its own empire, which became a great power and one of the largest states in Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The empire's defeat in wars and the loss of territories in the 1860s paved the way for the establishment of Austria-Hungary in 1867.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in 1914, Emperor Franz Joseph declared war on Serbia, which rapidly escalated into World War I.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The empire's defeat and subsequent collapse led to the proclamation of the Republic of German-Austria in 1918 and the First Austrian Republic in 1919.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] During the interwar period, anti-parliamentarian sentiments culminated in the formation of an Austrofascist dictatorship under Engelbert Dollfuss in 1934.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] A year before the outbreak of World War II, Austria was annexed into Nazi Germany by Adolf Hitler, and it became a sub-national division.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After its liberation in 1945 and a decade of Allied occupation, the country regained its sovereignty and declared its perpetual neutrality in 1955.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria is a semi-presidential representative democracy with a popularly elected president as head of state and a chancellor as head of government and chief executive.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria has the 13th highest nominal GDP per capita with high standards of living.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The country has been a member of the United Nations since 1955 and of the European Union since 1995.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] It hosts the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) and the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and is a founding member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and Interpol.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] It also signed the Schengen Agreement in 1995, and adopted the euro currency in 1999.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The native name for Austria, *Österreich*, derives from the Old High German *Ostarrîchi*, which meant "eastern realm", can be also translated as "eastern empire" or "eastern kingdom", and which first appeared in the "Ostarrîchi document" of 996.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This word is probably a translation of Medieval Latin *Marchia orientalis* into a local (Bavarian) dialect.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria was a prefecture of Bavaria created in 976.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The word "Austria" is a Latinisation of the German name and was first recorded in the 12th century.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] At the time, the Danube basin of Austria (Upper and Lower Austria) was the easternmost extent of Bavaria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The area that is now Austria was settled in pre-Roman times by various Celtic tribes, having been the core of the Hallstatt culture by the 6th century BC.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The city of Hallstatt, in fact, has the oldest archaeological evidence of the Celts in Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Celtic Kingdom of Noricum that included most of modern Austria and parts of modern Slovenia was conquered by the Roman Empire in 16 BC and made a province called Noricum which lasted until 476.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The regions of today's Austria which were not located within the province of Noricum were divided between the Roman provinces of Pannonia, which encompassed parts of eastern Austria, and Raetia, which encompassed the areas of present-day Vorarlberg and Tyrol.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Present-day Petronell-Carnuntum in eastern Austria was an important army camp turned capital city in what became known as the Pannonia Superior.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Carnuntum was home to 50,000 people for nearly 400 years.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the area was first invaded by the Germanic Rugii which made this region part of their "Rugiland".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 487, most of modern Austria was conquered by Odoacer, a barbarian soldier and statesman from the Middle Danube, which incorporated most of today's Austria in his Kingdom of Italy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] By 493, it was conquered by the Germanic Ostrogoths which created their own kingdom, the Ostrogothic Kingdom.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Following the Kingdom's fall the area was invaded by the Alemanni, Baiuvarii, Slavs, and Avars.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Charlemagne, King of the Franks, conquered the area in 788, encouraged colonisation, and introduced Christianity.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As part of Eastern Francia, the core areas that now encompass Austria were bequeathed to the house of Babenberg.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The area was known as the *marchia Orientalis* and was given to Leopold I in 976.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The first record showing the name Austria is from 996, where it is written as *Ostarrîchi*, referring to the territory of the Babenberg March.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1156, the Privilegium Minus elevated Austria to the status of a duchy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1192, the Babenbergs also acquired the Duchy of Styria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] With the death of Frederick II in 1246, the line of the Babenbergs was extinguished.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As a result, Ottokar II of Bohemia effectively assumed control of the duchies of Austria, Styria, and Carinthia.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] His reign came to an end with his defeat at Dürnkrut at the hands of Rudolph I of Germany in 1278.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Thereafter, until World War I, Austria's history was largely that of its ruling dynasty, the Habsburgs.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the 14th and 15th centuries, the Habsburgs began to accumulate other provinces in the vicinity of the Duchy of Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1438, Duke Albert V of Austria was chosen as the successor to his father-in-law, Emperor Sigismund.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Although Albert himself only reigned for a year, henceforth every emperor of the Holy Roman Empire was a Habsburg, with only one exception.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Habsburgs also began to accumulate territory far from the hereditary lands.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1477, Archduke Maximilian, only son of Emperor Frederick III, married the heiress Maria of Burgundy, thus acquiring most of the Netherlands for the family.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1496, his son Philip the Fair married Joanna the Mad, the heiress of Castile and Aragon, thus acquiring Spain and its Italian, African, Asian, and New World appendages for the Habsburgs.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1526, following the Battle of Mohács, Bohemia and the part of Hungary not occupied by the Ottomans came under Austrian rule.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Ottoman expansion into Hungary led to frequent conflicts between the two empires, particularly evident in the Long War of 1593 to 1606.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Turks made incursions into Styria nearly 20 times, of which some are cited as "burning, pillaging, and taking thousands of slaves".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In late September 1529, Suleiman the Magnificent launched the first siege of Vienna, which unsuccessfully ended, according to Ottoman historians, with the snowfalls of an early beginning winter.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] During the long reign of Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor following the successful defence of Vienna against the Turks in 1683, under the command of the King of Poland John III Sobieski, the Great Turkish War resulted in most of Hungary being controlled by Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This arrangement was formalized in the Treaty of Karlowitz in 1699.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor relinquished many of the gains the empire made in the previous years.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He enjoyed the imminent extinction of the House of Habsburg.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Charles VI was willing to offer concrete advantages in territory and authority in exchange for recognition of the Pragmatic Sanction of 1713.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Therefore, his daughter Maria Theresa was recognized as his heir.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] With the rise of Prussia, the Austria–Prussia rivalry began in Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria participated, together with Prussia and Russia, in the first and the third of the three Partitions of Poland in 1772 and 1795 respectively.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria engaged in war with Revolutionary France, as part of the First and Second Coalitions, and subsequently in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] From 1792 to 1801, the Austrians had suffered 754,700 casualties.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Hapsburg rulers of Austria and the Holy Roman Empire suffered successive defeats at the hands of Napoleon Bonaparte.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] To protect their status as an imperial dynasty after Napoleon proclaimed the French Empire, the Empire of Austria was founded in 1804, and to prevent Napoleon from claiming their previous Imperial throne, the Holy Roman Empire was abolished 1806.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1814, Austria was part of the coalition of Allied forces that invaded France and brought to an end the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian Empire emerged from the Congress of Vienna in 1815 as one of the continent's four dominant powers and a recognized great power.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The same year, the German Confederation (*Deutscher Bund*) was founded under the presidency of Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Because of unsolved social, political, and national conflicts, the German lands were shaken by the 1848 revolutions aiming to create a unified Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The possibilities for a unified Germany were: a Greater Germany or a Greater Austria or a German Confederation without Austria at all.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1864, Austria and Prussia fought together against Denmark and secured the independence from Denmark of the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As they could not agree on how the two duchies should be administered, though they fought the Austro-Prussian War in 1866.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Defeated by Prussia in the Battle of Königgrätz, Austria had to leave the German Confederation and no longer took part in German politics.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As Austria's Habsburg monarchy was not willing to join its German-speaking territory to the German Empire of 1871, and relinquish its non-German-speaking territories, the crown of the newly formed empire was offered to the Prussian King Friedrich Wilhelm IV.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] To settle issues lingering from the suppressed Hungarian Revolution of 1848, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, the *Ausgleich*, provided for a dual sovereignty, the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary, under Franz Joseph I.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian-Hungarian rule of this diverse empire included various groups, including Germans, Hungarians, Croats, Czechs, Poles, Rusyns, Serbs, Slovaks, Slovenes, and Ukrainians, as well as large Italian and Romanian communities.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As a result, ruling Austria-Hungary became increasingly difficult in an age of emerging nationalist movements, requiring considerable reliance on an expanded secret police.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Many Austrian Germans of all different social circles such as Georg Ritter von Schönerer promoted strong pan-Germanism in the hope of reinforcing an ethnic German identity amongst Austrian Germans and the annexation of Austria to Germany (*Anschluss*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Some Austrians such as Karl Lueger also used pan-Germanism as a form of populism to further their own political goals.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria's exclusion from Germany caused many Austrians a problem with their national identity and prompted the Social Democratic Leader Otto Bauer to state that it was "the conflict between our Austrian and German character".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Empire caused ethnic tension between the German Austrians and the other ethnic groups.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Many Austrians, especially those involved with the pan-German movements, desired a reinforcement of an ethnic German identity and hoped that the empire would collapse, which would allow an annexation of Austria by Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Many Austrian pan-German nationalists protested passionately against minister-president Kasimir Count Badeni's language decree of 1897, which made German and Czech co-official languages in Bohemia and required new government officials to be fluent in both languages.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This meant in practice that the civil service would almost exclusively hire Czechs because most middle-class Czechs spoke German but not the other way around.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The support of ultramontane Catholic politicians and clergy for this reform triggered the launch of the *Away from Rome* movement, which was initiated by supporters of Schönerer and called on "German" Christians to leave the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As the Second Constitutional Era began in the Ottoman Empire, Austria-Hungary took the opportunity to annex Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1908.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Over one million Austro-Hungarian soldiers died in World War I.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 21 October 1918, the elected German members of the *Reichsrat* (parliament of Imperial Austria) met in Vienna as the Provisional National Assembly for German Austria (*Provisorische Nationalversammlung für Deutschösterreich*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 30 October the assembly founded the Republic of German-Austria by appointing a government, called *Staatsrat*.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This new government was invited by the Emperor to take part in the decision on the planned armistice with Italy but refrained from this business.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This left the responsibility for the end of the war, on 3 November 1918, solely to the emperor and his government.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 11 November, the emperor, advised by ministers of the old and the new governments, declared he would not take part in state business any more; on 12 November, German-Austria, by law, declared itself to be a democratic republic and part of the new German republic.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The constitution, renaming the *Staatsrat* as *Bundesregierung* (federal government) and *Nationalversammlung* as *Nationalrat* (national council) was passed on 10 November 1920.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint-Germain of 1919 (for Hungary the Treaty of Trianon of 1920) confirmed and consolidated the new order of Central Europe which to a great extent had been established in November 1918, creating new states and altering others.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The German-speaking parts of Austria which had been part of Austria-Hungary were reduced to a rump state named the Republic of German-Austria (German: *Republik Deutschösterreich*), though excluding the predominantly German-speaking South Tyrol.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The desire for the annexation of Austria to Germany was a popular opinion shared by all social circles in both Austria and Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 12 November, German-Austria was declared a republic, and named Social Democrat Karl Renner as provisional chancellor.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On the same day it drafted a provisional constitution that stated that "German-Austria is a democratic republic" (Article 1) and "German-Austria is an integral part of the German Reich" (Article 2).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint Germain and the Treaty of Versailles explicitly forbade union between Austria and Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The treaties also forced German-Austria to rename itself as "Republic of Austria" which consequently led to the first Austrian Republic.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Over three million German-speaking Austrians found themselves living outside the new Austrian Republic as minorities in the newly formed or enlarged states of Czechoslovakia, Yugoslavia, Hungary, and Italy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] These included the provinces of South Tyrol, and German Bohemia.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The status of German Bohemia and Sudetenland later played a role in World War II.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The border between Austria and the Kingdom of Yugoslavia was settled with the Carinthian Plebiscite in October 1920 and allocated the major part of the territory of the former Austro-Hungarian Crownland of Carinthia to Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This set the border on the Karawanks mountain range, with many Slovenes remaining in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After the war, inflation began to devalue the Krone, which was still Austria's currency.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the autumn of 1922, Austria was granted an international loan supervised by the League of Nations.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The purpose of the loan was to avert bankruptcy, stabilise the currency, and improve Austria's general economic condition.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The loan meant that Austria passed from an independent state to the control exercised by the League of Nations.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1925, the *Austrian schilling* was introduced, replacing the Krone at a rate of 10,000:1.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Later, it was nicknamed the "Alpine dollar" due to its stability.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] From 1925 to 1929 the economy enjoyed a short high before nearly crashing after Black Tuesday.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The First Austrian Republic lasted until 1933, when Chancellor Engelbert Dollfuss, using what he called "self-switch-off of Parliament", established an autocratic regime tending towards Italian fascism.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The two big parties at this time, the Social Democrats and the Conservatives, had paramilitary armies; the Social Democrats' *Republikanischer Schutzbund* was now declared illegal, but was still operative as the 12–15 February 1934 Austrian Civil War broke out.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In February 1934, several members of the *Schutzbund* were executed, the Social Democratic party was outlawed, and many of its members were imprisoned or emigrated.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 1 May 1934, the Austrofascists imposed a new constitution ("Maiverfassung") which cemented Dollfuss's power, but on 25 July he was assassinated in an Austrian Nazi coup attempt.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] His successor Kurt Schuschnigg acknowledged the fact that Austria was a "German state" and he also believed that Austrians were "better Germans" but he wished that Austria would remain independent.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He announced a referendum on 9 March 1938, to be held on 13 March, concerning Austria's independence from Germany.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 12 March 1938, Austrian Nazis took over the government, while German troops occupied the country, which prevented Schuschnigg's referendum from taking place.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] 'joining' or 'connection') of Austria was officially declared.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Two days later, Austrian-born Adolf Hitler announced what he called the "reunification" of his home country with the "rest of the German Reich" on Vienna's Heldenplatz.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He established a referendum which confirmed the union with Germany in April 1938.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Parliamentary elections were held in Germany (including recently annexed Austria) on 10 April 1938.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] They were the final elections to the Reichstag during Nazi rule, and they took the form of a single-question referendum asking whether voters approved of a single Nazi-party list for the 813-member Reichstag, as well as the recent annexation of Austria (the *Anschluss*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Jews, Roma and Sinti were not allowed to vote.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Turnout in the election was officially 99.5%, with 98.9% voting "yes".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the case of Austria, Adolf Hitler's native soil, 99.71% of an electorate of 4,484,475 officially went to the ballots, with a positive tally of 99.73 percent.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Although most Austrians favoured the *Anschluss*, in certain parts of Austria, the German soldiers were not always welcomed with flowers and joy, especially in Vienna, which had Austria's largest Jewish population.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 13 March 1938, Austria was annexed by the Third Reich and ceased to exist as an independent country (the *Anschluss*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Aryanisation of the wealth of Jewish Austrians started immediately in mid-March, with a so-called "wild" (i.e. extra-legal) phase, but it was soon structured legally and bureaucratically so the assets which Jewish citizens possessed could be stripped from them.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] At that time, Adolf Eichmann, who grew up in Austria, was transferred to Vienna and ordered to persecute the Jews.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] During the November pogrom in 1938 ("Reichskristallnacht"), Jews and Jewish institutions such as synagogues were subjected to violent attacks in Vienna, Klagenfurt, Linz, Graz, Salzburg, Innsbruck and several cities in Lower Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Otto von Habsburg, a vehement opponent of the Nazis, the last Crown Prince of Austria-Hungary, an honorary citizen of hundreds of places in Austria and partly envisaged by Schuschnigg as a monarchical option, was in Belgium at the time.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He spoke out against the Anschluss and was then wanted by the Nazi regime and his property would have been expropriated and he would have been shot immediately if he were caught.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 1938, the Nazis renamed Austria the "Ostmark", a name which it had until 1942, when it was renamed the "Alpine and Danubian Gaue" (Alpen-und Donau-Reichsgaue).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the Reichsgau, besides the main camp KZ-Mauthausen, there were numerous sub-camps in all provinces where Jews and other prisoners were killed, tortured and exploited.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] At this time, because the territory was outside the operational radius of Allied aircraft, the armaments industry was greatly expanded through the forced labour of concentration camp prisoners, this was especially the case with regard to the manufacture of fighter planes, tanks and missiles.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Most of the resistance groups were soon crushed by the Gestapo.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] While the plans of the group around Karl Burian to blow up the Gestapo's headquarters in Vienna were uncovered, the important group around the later executed priest Heinrich Maier managed to contact the Allies.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This resistance group, which was in contact with the American secret service (OSS), soon provided information about mass executions and concentration camps such as Auschwitz.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The group's aim was to cause Nazi Germany to lose the war as quickly as possible and re-establish an independent Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Vienna fell on 13 April 1945, during the Soviet Vienna offensive, just before the total collapse of the Third Reich.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The invading Allied powers, in particular the Americans, planned for the supposed "Alpine Fortress Operation" of a national redoubt, that was largely to have taken place on Austrian soil in the mountains of the Eastern Alps.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] However, it never materialised because of the rapid collapse of the Reich.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] (The date is officially named the birthday of the second republic.) At the end of April, most of western and southern Austria were still under Nazi rule.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 1 May 1945, the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920, which had been terminated by dictator Dollfuss on 1 May 1934, was declared valid again.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The total number of Austrian military deaths from 1939 to 1945 was 260,000.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The total number of Jewish Austrian Holocaust victims was 65,000.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] About 140,000 Jewish Austrians had fled from the country in 1938–39.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Thousands of Austrians had taken part in serious Nazi crimes (hundreds of thousands of people died in the Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp alone), a fact which was officially acknowledged by Chancellor Franz Vranitzky in 1992.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Allied-occupied Austria was after World War II divided into military occupation zones.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria was governed by the Allied Commission for Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As stipulated in the Moscow Declaration of 1943 a subtle difference was seen in the treatment of Austria by the Allies.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian government, consisting of Social Democrats, Conservatives, and Communists resided in Vienna, which was surrounded by the Soviet zone.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This Austrian government was recognised by the allies of World War II in October 1945 despite concerns that Karl Renner could be Stalin's puppet.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 26 July 1946 the Austrian Parliament passed its first nationalization law and approximately 70 mining and manufacturing companies were seized by the Austrian state.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Ministry of Property Protection and Economic Planning (*Ministerium für Vermögenssicherung und Wirtschaftsplanung*) was responsible for directing the nationalized industries under the directorship of Minister Peter Krauland (party ÖVP).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 15 May 1955, after talks which lasted for years and were influenced by the Cold War Austria regained full independence by concluding the Austrian State Treaty with the allies of World War II.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, all occupation troops had left and Austria declared its *permanent neutrality* by an act of parliament.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This day is now Austria's National Day, a public holiday.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The status of Tyrol was a lingering problem between Austria and Italy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] To this day, there are 20 different squares in Austrian cities called "Südtiroler Platz" (South Tyrolean Square) in memory of the supposed loss of the Austrian territories.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Terrorist acts by the South Tyrolean independence movement have been documented in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] A great degree of autonomy was granted to Tyrol by the Italian national government.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic is based on the constitution of 1920 and 1929, which was reintroduced in 1945.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The system came to be characterised by *Proporz*, whereby most posts of political importance were split proportionately between members of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ) and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Interest group "chambers" with mandatory membership (e.g. for workers, business people, farmers) grew to considerable importance and were usually consulted in the legislative process, so hardly any legislation was passed that did not reflect widespread consensus.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Since 1945, governing via a single-party government has occurred twice: 1966–1970 (ÖVP) and 1970–1983 (SPÖ).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] During all other legislative periods, either a grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP or a "small coalition" (one of these two and a smaller party) ruled the country.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Kurt Waldheim, the former secretary-general of the United Nations, was elected President of Austria from 1986 to 1992.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He had been a Wehrmacht officer in the Second World War and was accused of war crimes.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Following a referendum in 1994, at which consent reached a majority of two-thirds, the country became a member of the European Union on 1 January 1995.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In reality, Austria is taking part in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy, participates in peacekeeping and peace creating tasks, and has become a member of NATO's "Partnership for Peace"; the constitution has been amended accordingly.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Since Liechtenstein joined the Schengen Area in 2011, none of Austria's neighbouring countries performs border controls towards it anymore.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria is a largely mountainous country because of its location in the Alps.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Central Eastern Alps, Northern Limestone Alps, and Southern Limestone Alps are all partly in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Of the total area of Austria (83,871 km2 or 32,383 sq mi), only about a quarter can be considered low-lying, and only 32% of the country is below 500 metres (1,640 ft).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Alps of western Austria give way somewhat into low lands and plains in the eastern part of the country.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria lies between latitudes 46° and 49° N, and longitudes 9° and 18° E.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] It can be divided into five areas, the biggest being the Eastern Alps, which constitute 62% of the nation's total area.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian foothills at the base of the Alps and the Carpathians account for about 12% and the foothills in the east and areas surrounding the periphery of the Pannoni low country amount to about 12% of the total landmass.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The second greater mountain area (much lower than the Alps) is situated in the north.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Known as the Austrian granite plateau, it is located in the central area of the Bohemian Mass and accounts for 10% of Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian portion of the Vienna basin makes up the remaining 4%.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In Austria, forest cover is about 47% of the total land area, equivalent to 3,899,150 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 3,775,670 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 2,227,500 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,671,500 hectares (ha).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 2% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and about 23% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] For the year 2015, 18% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 82% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Phytogeographically, Austria belongs to the Central European province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Austria can be subdivided into four ecoregions: the Central European mixed forests, Pannonian mixed forests, Alps conifer and mixed forests, and Western European broadleaf forests.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 3.55/10, ranking it 149th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The greater part of Austria lies in the cool/temperate climate zone, where humid westerly winds predominate.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] With nearly three-quarters of the country dominated by the Alps, the alpine climate is predominant.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the east—in the Pannonian Plain and along the Danube valley—the climate shows continental features with less rain than the alpine areas.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Although Austria is cold in the winter (−10 to 0 °C), summer temperatures can be relatively high, with average temperatures in the mid-20s and a highest temperature of 40.5 °C (105 °F) in August 2013.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification Austria has the following climate types: humid subtropical (Cfa), oceanic (Cfb), cool/warm-summer humid continental (Dfb), subarctic/subalpine (Dfc), tundra/alpine (ET), and ice-cap (EF).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria may experience very cold, severe winters, but most of the time they are only around as cold as those in somewhat comparable climate zones, for example, Southern Scandinavia or Eastern Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As well, at higher altitudes, summers are usually considerably cooler than in the valleys/lower altitudes.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The subarctic and tundra climates seen around the Alps are much warmer in winter than what is normal elsewhere due in part to the Oceanic influence on this part of Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Climate change in Austria has already caused temperature rises of almost 2 °C since 1880, and temperatures are expected to increase further while heat waves become more common.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Extreme precipitation events have become more frequent, and associated floods and landslides could threaten Austria's electricity supply security.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria's mountainous regions are highly sensitive to climate change and are experiencing reduced snowfall, earlier snowmelt and glacier loss.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Parliament of Austria is located in Vienna, the country's capital and most populous city.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria became a federal, representative democratic republic through the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic with its nine states is based on the constitution of 1920, amended in 1929, which was re-enacted on 1 May 1945.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The president of Austria is the head of state.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The president is directly elected by popular majority vote, with a run-off between the top-scoring candidates if necessary.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The chancellor of Austria is head of the government.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The chancellor is selected by the president and tasked with forming a government based on the partisan composition of the lower house of parliament.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The government can be removed from office by either a presidential decree or by vote of no confidence in the lower chamber of parliament, the *Nationalrat*.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Voting for the president and for the parliament used to be compulsory in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The compulsion was abolished in steps from 1982 to 2004.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria's parliament consists of two chambers.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The voting age was lowered from 18 to 16 in 2007.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] While there is a general threshold of 4% of the vote for all parties in federal elections (*Nationalratswahlen*) to participate in the proportional allocation of seats, there remains the possibility of being elected to a seat directly in one of the 43 regional electoral districts (*Direktmandat*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Nationalrat is the dominant chamber in the legislative process in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] However, the upper house of parliament, the *Bundesrat*, has a limited right of veto (the Nationalrat can—in almost all cases—ultimately pass the respective bill by voting a second time; this is referred to as a *Beharrungsbeschluss*, lit.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] A constitutional convention, called the *Österreich -Konvent* was convened on 30 June 2003 to consider reforms to the constitution, but failed to produce a proposal that would command a two-thirds majority in the Nationalrat, the margin necessary for constitutional amendments or reforms.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] While the bicameral Parliament and the Government constitute the legislative and executive branches, respectively, the courts are the third branch of Austrian state powers.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Constitutional Court exerts considerable influence on the political system because of its power to invalidate legislation and ordinances that are not in compliance with the Constitution.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Since 1995, the European Court of Justice may overrule Austrian decisions in all matters defined in the laws of the European Union.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria also implements the decisions of the European Court of Human Rights, since the European Convention on Human Rights is part of the Austrian constitution.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After the general election held in October 2006, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) emerged as the strongest party, and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) came in second, having lost about 8 Percentage points of its previous polling.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Political realities prohibited any of the two major parties from forming a coalition with smaller parties.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In January 2007 the ÖVP and SPÖ formed a grand coalition with Alfred Gusenbauer (SPÖ) as Chancellor.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The election in September 2008 further weakened both major parties (SPÖ 29.3 % and ÖVP 26.0 %).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] They formed a coalition with Werner Faymann (SPÖ) as Chancellor (First Faymann government).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Green Party came in third with 11% of the vote.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The FPÖ and the deceased Jörg Haider's new party Alliance for the Future of Austria, both on the political right, were strengthened during the election but taken together received less than 20% of the vote.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 11 October 2008, Jörg Haider died in a car accident.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In the legislative elections of 2013, the Social Democratic Party received 27% of the vote and 52 seats; the People's Party 24% and 47 seats, thus controlling together the majority of the seats.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Freedom Party received 40 seats and 21% of the votes, while the Greens received 12% and 24 seats.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Two new parties, Stronach and the NEOS, received less than 10% of the vote, and 11 and nine seats respectively.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 17 May 2016, Christian Kern from Social Democrats (SPÖ) was sworn in as the new chancellor.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He continued governing in a "grand coalition" with the conservative People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He took the office after the former chancellor, also from SPÖ, Werner Faymann's resignation.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 26 January 2017, Alexander Van der Bellen was sworn in as the mostly ceremonial – but symbolically significant – role of Austrian president.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] After the Grand Coalition broke in Spring 2017 a snap election was proclaimed for October 2017.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) with its new young leader Sebastian Kurz emerged as the largest party in the National Council, winning 31.5% of votes and 62 of the 183 seats.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) finished second with 52 seats and 26.9% votes, slightly ahead of the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ), which received 51 seats and 26 percent.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The ÖVP decided to form a coalition with the FPÖ.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The new government between the centre-right wing and the right-wing populist party under the new chancellor Sebastian Kurz was sworn in on 18 December 2017, but the coalition government later collapsed in the wake of the "Ibiza" corruption scandal and new elections were called for 29 September 2019.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The elections led to another landslide victory (37.5 percent) of the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) which formed a coalition government with the reinvigorated (13.9 percent) Greens, which was sworn in with Kurz as chancellor on 7 January 2020.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 11 October 2021, Chancellor Sebastian Kurz resigned following pressure from a corruption scandal.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] He was succeeded by Foreign Minister Alexander Schallenberg of the ÖVP.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] However, Schallenberg stepped down after less than two months, and Karl Nehammer was sworn in as chancellor on 6 December 2021, making him Austria's third conservative leader in two months.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The ÖVP and the Greens continued to govern together.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Following the election on 29 September 2024, coalition negotiations between the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS collapsed, leading to Nehammer's resignation.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Schallenberg stepped in as interim chancellor for the second time.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Attempts to form an ÖVP-FPÖ coalition also failed.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Eventually, the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS reached an agreement, forming a coalition government with Christian Stocker (ÖVP) as chancellor (Stocker government).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria is a federal republic consisting of nine states (Austrian German: *Bundesländer*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The states are sub-divided into districts (*Bezirke*) and statutory cities (*Statutarstädte*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Districts are subdivided into municipalities (*Gemeinden*).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Statutory Cities have the competencies otherwise granted to both districts and municipalities.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Vienna is unique in that it is both a city and a state.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The European Commission's Directorate-General for Translation calls the states *provinces*.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The 1955 Austrian State Treaty ended the occupation of Austria following World War II and recognised Austria as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, the Federal Assembly passed a constitutional article in which "Austria declares of her own free will her perpetual neutrality".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The second section of this law stated that "in all future times Austria will not join any military alliances and will not permit the establishment of any foreign military bases on her territory".
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Since then, Austria has shaped its foreign policy on the basis of neutrality, but rather different from the neutrality of Switzerland.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria began to reassess its definition of neutrality following the fall of the Soviet Union, granting overflight rights for the UN-sanctioned action against Iraq in 1991, and since 1995, it has developed participation in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Also in 1995, it joined NATO's Partnership for Peace (although it was careful to do so only after Russia joined) and subsequently participated in peacekeeping missions in Bosnia.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Meanwhile, the only part of the Constitutional Law on Neutrality of 1955 still fully valid is not to allow foreign military bases in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria signed the UN's Nuclear Weapon Ban Treaty, which was opposed by all NATO members.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The manpower of the Austrian Armed Forces (Austrian German: *Bundesheer*) mainly relies on conscription.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] All males who have reached the age of eighteen and are found fit have to serve a six months compulsory military service, followed by an eight-year reserve obligation.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Both males and females at the age of sixteen are eligible for voluntary service.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Conscientious objection is legally acceptable and those who claim this right are obliged to serve an institutionalised nine months civilian service instead.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Since 1998, women volunteers have been allowed to become professional soldiers.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Austria is a landlocked country and has no navy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In 2012, Austria's defence expenditures corresponded to approximately 0.8% of its GDP.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Army currently has about 26,000 soldiers, of whom about 12,000 are conscripts.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] As head of state, the Austrian president is nominally the commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Command of the Austrian Armed Forces is exercised by the minister of defence, as of May 2020: Klaudia Tanner.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] This assistance came to an end when Hungary and Slovakia joined the EU Schengen Area in 2008, for all intents and purposes abolishing "internal" border controls between treaty states.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Some politicians have called for a prolongation of this mission, but the legality of this is heavily disputed.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] In accordance with the Austrian constitution, armed forces may only be deployed in a limited number of cases, mainly to defend the country and aid in cases of national emergency, such as in the wake of natural disasters.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] They may only exceptionally be used as auxiliary police forces.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Within its self-declared status of permanent neutrality, Austria has a tradition of engaging in UN-led peacekeeping and other humanitarian missions.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] The Austrian Forces Disaster Relief Unit (AFDRU), in particular, an all-volunteer unit with close ties to civilian specialists (e.g. rescue dog handlers) enjoys a reputation as a quick (standard deployment time is 10 hours) and efficient SAR unit.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] Currently, larger contingents of Austrian forces are deployed in Bosnia and Kosovo.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Austria is the 3rd most peaceful country in the world.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria consistently ranks high in terms of GDP per capita, due to its highly industrialised economy, and well-developed social market economy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Until the 1980s, many of Austria's largest industry firms were nationalised; in recent years, however, privatisation has reduced state holdings to a level comparable to other European economies.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Labour movements are particularly influential, exercising a large influence on labour politics and decisions related to the expansion of the economy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Next to a highly developed industry, international tourism is the most important part of the economy of Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Germany has historically been the main trading partner of Austria, making it vulnerable to rapid changes in the German economy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Since Austria became a member state of the European Union, it has gained closer ties to other EU economies.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Membership of the EU has drawn an influx of foreign investors attracted by Austria's access to the single European market and proximity to the aspiring economies of the European Union.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] At least 67% of Austria's imports come from other European Union member states.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The 2008 financial crisis led to the Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International to be purchased in December 2009 by the government for 1 euro owing to credit difficulties, thus wiping out the €1.63bn of BayernLB.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] As of February 2014, the HGAA situation was unresolved, causing Chancellor Werner Faymann to warn that its failure would be comparable to the 1931 Creditanstalt event.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria indicated on 16 November 2010 that it would withhold the December instalment of its contribution to the EU bailout of Greece, citing the material worsening of the Greek debt situation and the apparent inability of Greece to collect the level of tax receipts it had previously promised.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Since the fall of communism, Austrian companies have been quite active players and consolidators in Eastern Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Between 1995 and 2010, 4,868 mergers and acquisitions with a total known value of 163 billion EUR with the involvement of Austrian firms have been announced.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Tourism in Austria accounts for almost 9% of its gross domestic product.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2007, Austria ranked 9th worldwide in international tourism receipts, with 18.9 billion US$.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In international tourist arrivals, Austria ranked 12th with 20.8 million tourists.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 1972 the country began construction of a nuclear power plant to produce electricity at Zwentendorf on the River Danube, following a unanimous vote in parliament.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] However, in 1978 a referendum voted approximately 50.5% against nuclear power, 49.5% for, and parliament subsequently unanimously passed a law forbidding the use of nuclear power to generate electricity although the nuclear power plant had already finished.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria currently produces more than half of its electricity by hydropower.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Together with other renewable energy sources such as wind power, solar power, and biomass, the electricity supply from renewable energy amounts to 62.89 percent.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Compared to most European countries, Austria is ecologically well endowed.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Its biocapacity (or biological natural capital) is more than double of the world average: In 2016 Austria had 3.8 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, compared to the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] By contrast, in 2016 they used 6.0 global hectares of biocapacity which amounts to Austria's ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] This means that Austrians use about 60% more biocapacity than Austria contains.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] As a result, Austria is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Rail transport in Austria is primarily provided by the national carrier Austrian Federal Railways (*Österreichische Bundesbahnen*, ÖBB).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] It operates most commuter rail systems and long-distance trains.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria's population was estimated to be 9,220,882 in April 2026 by Statistik Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The population of the capital, Vienna, exceeds 2 million, representing about a quarter of the country's population.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] It is known for its cultural offerings and high standard of living.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] All other cities have fewer than 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] According to Statistik Austria, at the beginning of 2024, there were 1.8 million foreign-born residents in Austria, corresponding to 22.3% of the total population.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] There are more than 620,100 descendants of foreign-born immigrants.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] There are a group of legally recognized indigenous non-German speaking minorities, like Carinthian Slovenes, or the approximately 25,000 Romani people.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) in 2023 was estimated at 1.32 children born per woman, below the replacement rate of 2.1, it remains considerably below the high of 4.83 children born per woman in 1873.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2015, 42.1% of births were to unmarried women.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria had the 14th oldest population in the world in 2020, with the average age of 44.5 years.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The life expectancy in 2024 was estimated at 82.3 years, placing Austria above the EU average of 81.7 years.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2024, Statistik Austria estimated that the population will grow to 10,179,834 people by 2080, primarily driven by immigration.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The official language of Austria is German, as specified by article 8 of its constitution of 1920.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The written form of German in Austria and in the Italian South Tyrol region is Austrian German, or simply Austrian, a variety of Standard High German; it has been standardized in Austria since 1951, when the Ministry of Education, Science and Research published the *Österreichisches Wörterbuch*.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] This standard form, however, is used primarily in education and for government publications, announcements and websites; the *de facto* common spoken languages of Austria are not the Austrian German as taught in schools but rather the Bavarian and Alemannic dialects.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] These are two mutually intelligible Upper German local languages or collections of dialects that are understood, with varying degrees of difficulty, by each other as well as by speakers of non-Austrian German dialects.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The Austrian state of Carinthia is home to a significant indigenous Slovene-speaking minority, while in the easternmost state, Burgenland (formerly part of the Hungarian portion of Austria-Hungary), there are significant Hungarian- and Croatian-speaking minorities.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Burgenland Croatian, Hungarian, and Slovene are also recognized as official languages beside German in parts of Carinthia and Burgenland.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] According to census information published by Statistik Austria, there were a total of 710,926 foreign nationals living in Austria in 2001.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Of these, the largest by far were 283,334 foreign nationals from the former Yugoslavia (of whom 135,336 spoke Serbian; 105,487 Croatian; 31,591 Bosnian — i.e., 272,414 Austrian resident native speakers in total, plus 6,902 Slovenian and 4,018 Macedonian speakers).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The predominant historic ethnicity of Austrians is German speaking, which is closely related to people from neighbouring countries Germany, Liechtenstein, and German-speaking Switzerland.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austrian ethnicity has considerable convergence with non-German speaking populations to the east and south of Austria, particularly in Vienna, through its position and role in Eastern Europe today and as the capital of the former multi-ethnic Habsburg Empire.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] This is reflected in the officially recognized non-German speaking indigneous populations of Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] An estimated 13,000 to 40,000 Slovenes in the Austrian state Carinthia (the Carinthian Slovenes) as well as Croats (about 30,000) and Hungarians in Burgenland were recognised as a minority and have had special rights following the Austrian State Treaty (*Staatsvertrag*) of 1955.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Since 1994 the Romani people and Sinti have been an officially recognised ethnic minority in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria's people who are of non-Austrian descent, many come from surrounding countries, especially from the former East Bloc nations.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Guest workers *(Gastarbeiter)* and their descendants, as well as refugees from the Yugoslav wars and other conflicts, also form an important minority group in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The largest single immigrant group in Austria are Germans, only collectively surpassed by people from ex-Jugoslavian countries.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The largest group of people born in ex-Jugoslavian countries are from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The next biggest group are people born in Turkey.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] People from Turkey are closely followed by people from Serbia.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Serbs form one of the largest ethnic groups in Austria, numbering around 300,000 people.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Historically, Serbian immigrants moved to Austria during the time of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, when Vojvodina was under Imperial control.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Following World War II the number of Serbs expanded again, and today the community is very large.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The Austrian Serbian Society was founded in 1936.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Today, Serbs in Austria are mainly found in Vienna, Salzburg, and Graz.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria was historically a strongly Catholic country as the centre of the Habsburg monarchy, which championed Catholicism.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2001, about 74% of Austria's population were registered as Catholic, while about 5% considered themselves Protestants.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austrian Christians, both Catholic and Protestant, are obliged to pay a mandatory membership fee (calculated by income – about 1%) to their churches; this payment is called the *Kirchenbeitrag* ("ecclesiastical contribution").
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] From the second half of the 20th century, the number of adherents and churchgoers has declined.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Data for 2023 list 4,638,000 members of the Catholic Church, or about 50% of the total Austrian population, yet Sunday church attendance was only 347,000, or 3.7% of the total Austrian population.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Additionally, the Lutheran church recorded a loss of 74,421 adherents between 2001 and 2016.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The 2001 census reported that about 12% of the population declared themselves without a religion; according to ecclesiastical information, this share had grown to 20% by 2015 and further increased to 22.4% (1,997,700 people) in 2021.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Of the remaining population, about 340,000 were registered as members of various Muslim communities in 2001, originating chiefly from Turkey, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Kosovo; the number of Muslims doubled in the fifteen years to 2016, to 700,000, and reached 745,600 in 2021.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2021, another 436,700 residents of Austria (mostly Serbs) were members of Eastern Orthodox Churches, 26,600 were Buddhists, 10,100 were Hindus, about 21,800 were active Jehovah's Witnesses, and 5,400 were Jews.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Education in Austria is federally governed by the Ministry of Education, Science and Research, with administration handled by individual states.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] School attendance is mandatory for nine years, typically from ages six to fifteen.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Kindergarten is available for children aged three to six, with compulsory attendance starting at five.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] While part-time daycare is free nationwide for this age group, Vienna and Burgenland offer free all-day care.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] By 2018, about 90% of children between three and five attended early childhood education.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Volksschule or Grundschule starts at age six and lasts for four years, with an average class size of 18 pupils.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Secondary education is divided into different tracks: Mittelschule, which focuses on vocational training, and Allgemeinbildende Höhere Schule, an academic secondary school that prepares students for university through the Matura examination.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] At age 10, students, parents, and teachers decide the most suitable path based on the child's abilities and interests.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria is also known for its dual education system, which integrates theoretical learning with practical training; in 2021, 34.1% of secondary level II students participated in this system.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria allocated 4.9% of its GDP to education in 2021, with spending per student averaging US$16,734.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] German proficiency is essential in public schools, and children's language skills are assessed using the MIKA-D test upon admission.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Students who require additional support receive targeted language assistance to facilitate integration into the educational system.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Even though Austria has a 0.9 health index and a life expectancy of 81 years, the country still faces numerous problems when it comes to health, one example being that 2 in 5 Austrians have a chronic condition.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] One of the most costly health services in the EU is located in Austria.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In 2019, health spending per capita ranked third in the EU.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Health-related out-of-pocket expenditures are higher than the EU average.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] With 5.2 physicians per 1,000 inhabitants, Austria has among the highest physician density in OECD countries.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Overall, the country has 271 hospitals with a total of 45,596 physicians (data from 2017), about 54% of which work (also or primarily) in hospitals.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Although Austria has the second highest physician rate in the EU, a large share of physicians is tropical to retirement age (55 years and older), and may thus be at a higher risk of developing severe conditions in a specimen of COVID-19 infection.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The number of nurses in Austria has been subject to debate in recent years with regard to definitions of qualifications and their interpretation in cross-country comparisons.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] A new mandatory health professional registry was set up in 2018.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] However, due to the elapsing of the COVID-19 pandemic in early 2020, compulsory registration has been suspended.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] This implies that professional activities in long-term superintendency are moreover possible without registration until the end of the pandemic by late spring 2022 (Transition without the pandemic is still to be defined).
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria's past as a European power and its cultural environment generated a broad contribution to various forms of art, most notably among them music.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria was the birthplace of many famous composers such as Joseph Haydn, Michael Haydn, Franz Liszt, Franz Schubert, Anton Bruckner, Johann Strauss Sr., and Johann Strauss Jr., as well as members of the Second Viennese School such as Arnold Schoenberg, Anton Webern, and Alban Berg.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was born in Salzburg, then an independent Church Principality of the Holy Roman Empire, which later became part of Austria, and much of Mozart's career was spent in Vienna.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Vienna was for a long time an important centre of musical innovation.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] 18th- and 19th-century composers were drawn to the city due to the patronage of the Habsburgs, and made Vienna the European capital of classical music.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] During the Baroque period, Slavic and Hungarian folk forms influenced Austrian music.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Vienna's status began its rise as a cultural centre in the early 16th century and was focused around instruments, including the lute.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Ludwig van Beethoven spent the better part of his life in Vienna.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria's current national anthem, attributed to Mozart, was chosen after World War II to replace the traditional Austrian anthem by Joseph Haydn.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austrian Herbert von Karajan was principal conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic for 35 years.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] He is generally regarded as one of the greatest conductors of the 20th century, and he was a dominant figure in European classical music from the 1960s until his death.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria was the cradle of numerous scientists with international reputation.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Among them are Ludwig Boltzmann, Ernst Mach, Victor Franz Hess, and Christian Doppler, prominent scientists in the 19th century.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In the 20th century, contributions by Lise Meitner, Erwin Schrödinger, and Wolfgang Pauli to nuclear research and quantum mechanics were key to these areas' development during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Prominent present-day quantum physicists are Anton Zeilinger and Peter Zoller renown for important developments in quantum optics and quantum information.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In addition to physicists, Austria was the birthplace of two of the most noteworthy philosophers of the 20th century, Ludwig Wittgenstein and Karl Popper.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In addition to them, biologists Gregor Mendel and Konrad Lorenz as well as mathematician Kurt Gödel and engineers such as Ferdinand Porsche and Siegfried Marcus were Austrians.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Bertha von Suttner became the first woman to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, and the first Austrian laureate.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] A focus of Austrian science has always been medicine and psychology, starting in medieval times with Paracelsus.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Eminent physicians like Theodore Billroth, Clemens von Pirquet, and Anton von Eiselsberg have built upon the achievements of the 19th-century Vienna School of Medicine.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria was home to Sigmund Freud, founder of psychoanalysis, Alfred Adler, founder of Individual psychology, psychologists Paul Watzlawick and Hans Asperger, and psychiatrist Viktor Frankl.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria was ranked 17th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, but it declined to the 19th rank according to GII 2025.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The Austrian School of Economics, which is prominent as one of the main competitive directions for economic theory, is related to Austrian economists Carl Menger, Joseph Schumpeter, Eugen von Böhm-Bawerk, Ludwig von Mises, and Friedrich Hayek.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Other noteworthy Austrian-born émigrés include the econimic anthropologist Karl Paul Polanyi, management thinker Peter Drucker, sociologist Paul Felix Lazarsfeld, and scientist Sir Gustav Nossal.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria's cuisine is derived from that of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austrian cuisine is rooted in the long-standing traditions of the imperial court kitchen ("Hofküche"), which evolved over centuries within the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] It is distinguished by its refined and well-balanced preparation of beef and pork, as well as by a wide variety of vegetable-based dishes.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In addition to native regional traditions, the cuisine has been influenced by Hungarian, Czech, Polish, Jewish, Italian, Balkan, and French cuisines, from which both dishes and methods of food preparation have often been borrowed.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The Austrian cuisine is therefore one of the most multicultural and transcultural in Europe.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Typical Austrian dishes include Wiener Schnitzel, Schweinsbraten, Kaiserschmarren, Knödel, Sachertorte, and Tafelspitz.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] There are also Kärntner Kasnudeln, which are pockets of dough filled with Topfen, potatoes, herbs and peppermint which are boiled and served with a butter sauce.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Kasnudeln are traditionally served with a salad.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The sugar block dispenser Pez was invented in Austria, as well as Mannerschnitten.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Austria is also famous for its Mozartkugeln and its coffee tradition.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] With over 8 kg per year it has the sixth highest per capita coffee consumption worldwide.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Beer is sold in 0.2-litre (a *Pfiff*), 0.3-litre (a *Seidel*, *kleines Bier* or *Glas Bier*) and 0.5-litre (a *Krügerl* or *großes Bier* or *Halbe*) measures.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] At festivals one litre *Maß* and two-litre *Doppelmaß* in the Bavarian style are also dispensed.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The most popular types of beer are lager (known as *Märzen* in Austria), naturally cloudy *Zwicklbier* and wheat beer.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] At holidays like Christmas and Easter bock beer is also available.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The most important wine-producing areas are in Lower Austria, Burgenland, Styria, and Vienna.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The Grüner Veltliner grape provides some of Austria's most notable white wines and Zweigelt is the most widely planted red wine grape.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] In Upper Austria, Lower Austria, Styria, and Carinthia, *Most*, a type of cider or perry, is widely produced.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] A Schnapps of typically up to 60% alcohol or fruit brandy is drunk, which in Austria is made from a variety of fruits, for example apricots and rowanberries.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The produce of small private schnapps distilleries, of which there are about 20,000 in Austria, is known as *Selbstgebrannter* or *Hausbrand*.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Local soft drinks such as Almdudler are very popular around the country as an alternative to alcoholic beverages.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Another popular drink is the so-called "Spezi", a mix between Coca-Cola and the original formula of Orange Fanta or the more locally renowned Frucade.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Red Bull, the highest-selling energy drink in the world, was introduced by Dietrich Mateschitz, an Austrian entrepreneur.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Due to the mountainous terrain, alpine skiing is a prominent sport in Austria and is extremely valuable in the promotion and economic growth of the country.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Similar sports such as snowboarding or ski-jumping are also widely popular.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] Bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton are also popular events with a permanent track located in Igls, which hosted bobsleigh and luge competitions for the 1964 and 1976 Winter Olympics held in Innsbruck.
[src:advanced-economy/austria-p02] The first Winter Youth Olympics in 2012 were held in Innsbruck as well.
